aVBut what do teachers like Ms. Russ do to succeed with young people
p132
aVlike the ones I study?
p133
aVI propose three strategies.
p134
aVThe first:
p135
aVlet's get rid of our deficit perspective in education.
p136
aV"These people come from a culture of violence,
p137
aVa culture of poverty.
p138
aVThese people are at-risk; these people are truant.
p139
aVThese people are empty containers for us to fill with knowledge.
p140
aVThey have the problems,
p141
aVwe have the solutions."
p142
aVNumber two.
p143
aVLet's value the stories that young people bring to the schoolhouse.
p144
aVTheir stories of overcoming insurmountable odds are so powerful.
p145
aVAnd I know you know some of these stories.
p146
aVThese very same stories and experiences
p147
aValready have grit, character and resilience in them.
p148
aVSo let's help young people refine those stories.
p149
aVLet's help them be proud of who they are,
p150
aVbecause our education system welcomes their families, their cultures,
p151
aVtheir communities
p152
aVand the skill set they've learned to survive.
p153
aVAnd of course the third strategy being the most important:
p154
aVresources.
p155
aVWe have to provide adequate resources to young people.
p156
aVGrit alone isn't going to cut it.
p157
aVYou can sit there and tell me all you want,
p158
aV"Hey man, pick yourself up by the bootstraps."
p159
aVBut if I was born without any straps on my boots \u2014
p160
aa(lp161
V(Laughter)
p162
aa(lp163
VHow am I supposed to pick myself up?
